communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Coalie
communications.communication:
Dear Department of the Interior:

This is a request for records under the Freedom of Information Act.

RECORDS REQUESTED:

Please produce all records related to DOI’s coal mascot, “Coalie.” Many responsive records may be located within the Office of Surface Mining Reclamation & Enforcement (OSMRE), but the scope of my request is agency-wide.

Specifically, I request the following records:

1. Please produce all records related to the conception, creation, and design of the Coalie mascot. Please include any contracts or design concepts (e.g. sketches) in your production, as well as any records related to DOI's decision to create a coal mascot in the first place.

2. If any image of Coalie was created using AI, please produce all AI prompts that were used in the course of creating the image. Please also produce all AI image results that were generated but not ultimately used. 

3. Please produce all Coalie-related promotional items, educational items, or tchotchkes, that took the form of records, such as trading cards, posters, videos, worksheets, or books (including but not limited to coloring books, activity books, or comic books).

4. Please produce all records related to the conception, creation, design, and use of any wearable Coalie costume. Responsive records would include contracts for the design or production of such a costume; design proposals or sketches; correspondence with the designer or manufacturer; and any guidelines related to the use of or care for the costume.

5. Please produce all communications related to Coalie. This includes internal agency communications, as well as communications sent to or received from non-DOI people, agencies, or entities (public or private).

6. Please produce any plans or guidelines for how the Coalie mascot will be used.

7. Please produce all documents in which the Coalie mascot appears, including electronic records such as social media posts.

REQUEST FOR FEE WAIVER:

The requested documents will be made available to the general public online for free, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am working on a project examining the history, creation, evolution, and use of mascots across the federal government—because, like many others, I find them fascinating and weirdly delightful. Thus, I respectfully request that any fees related to this request be waived. If you do decide to charge me fees, please notify me in advance if you expect those fees to exceed $25.

CONCLUSION

Thank you for your prompt attention to and processing of this request.

title: Florida Public Records Request: FACES Facial Recognition System (Okaloosa County Sheriff's Department)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Public Records Law (Chapter 119, Florida Statutes), I hereby request the following records related to Okaloosa County Sheriffs Department's use of and access to the Pinellas County Sheriff's Office Face Analysis Comparison & Examination System (FACES) and related surveillance technologies:

1. FACES SYSTEM ACCESS POLICIES AND PROCEDURES:
   - All current written policies governing the department's use of the FACES facial recognition system
   - All memoranda of understanding (MOUs), memoranda of agreement (MOAs), interagency agreements, or contracts with Pinellas County Sheriff's Office or any other entity related to FACES access
   - Training materials provided to personnel authorized to use FACES
   - Standard operating procedures (SOPs) for conducting FACES searches
   - Documents describing civil rights protections, limitations on use, or oversight mechanisms for FACES searches

2. ADMINISTRATIVE LOGS AND USAGE RECORDS:
   - Organization Audit reports from FACES showing searches conducted by department personnel for the period of January 1st, 2026 to the date this request is processed if available
   - Documents sufficient to show:
     * Total number of FACES searches conducted by the department
     * User logs identifying which personnel conducted searches (names may be redacted if required by law, but please include badge numbers or employee IDs)
     * Case numbers or incident reports associated with each search
     * Stated reasons or justifications for each search
     * Any internal audit reports reviewing FACES usage for compliance or misuse

3. INTEGRATION AND RELATED TECHNOLOGIES:
   - All contracts, agreements, purchase orders, invoices, or correspondence with FUSUS/Axon or any entity related to FUSUS system implementation or integration
   - Documents describing any integration between FACES and the FUSUS platform or any other real-time surveillance systems
   - Technical specifications or system architecture documents showing how FACES connects or shares data with other surveillance technologies including but not limited to:
     * FUSUS real-time camera integration platform
     * Automated License Plate Readers (ALPRs)
     * Predictive policing systems
     * Body-worn cameras
     * ShotSpotter or other gunshot detection systems
     * Private camera registries
   - Any assessments, reports, or internal communications discussing the integration of FACES with other surveillance technologies
   - Documents describing any real-time crime center operations that utilize FACES

4. PERFORMANCE AND ACCURACY:
   - Any internal assessments, audits, or external reports evaluating the accuracy, effectiveness, or reliability of FACES
   - Documents addressing known error rates, particularly regarding demographic disparities
   - Any false positive reports or case files where FACES identification was determined to be incorrect

5. POLICY UPDATES AND OVERSIGHT:
   - Communications with Pinellas County Sheriff's Office regarding policy updates or requirements implemented in 2024
   - Documents related to any citizen oversight, internal affairs reviews, or complaints regarding FACES usage
   - Any reports provided to elected officials, oversight bodies, or the public regarding FACES usage

================================================================================

IMPORTANT CLARIFICATION REGARDING SCOPE OF REQUEST:

This request does NOT seek:
- Personally identifiable information (PII) of individuals who have been subjects of searches or investigations, including names, addresses, dates of birth, social security numbers, or biometric data of searched individuals
- Photographs, facial recognition images, or biometric templates of any individuals in the FACES database
- Specific investigative techniques, methodologies, or operational tactics that would compromise ongoing or future investigations
- Information that would reveal the identity of confidential informants or undercover officers

This request DOES seek:
- Policies, procedures, and governance documents regarding system use
- Aggregate statistical data and anonymized audit logs showing usage patterns, search volume, and compliance
- System integration information at an architectural level (what systems connect to what) without revealing specific security vulnerabilities
- Public accountability records such as oversight reports, accuracy assessments, and policy compliance reviews

I am seeking information about the governance, oversight, financial arrangements, and operational policies surrounding these technologies—not information about specific individuals, active investigations, or sensitive law enforcement techniques. All personal identifying information of subjects, victims, witnesses, or confidential sources should be redacted as required by law.

If any responsive records contain both exempt and non-exempt information, I request that you provide the non-exempt portions with appropriate redactions, as required by Florida Statutes § 119.07(1)(d).

================================================================================

FORMAT AND FEE WAIVER REQUEST:

Please provide the requested records in their original electronic, machine-readable format. For audit reports and logs, please provide data in .csv, .xlsx, or another database format if available. For policy documents, PDF format is acceptable.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. This request is made in the public interest to promote transparency and accountability regarding the use of facial recognition technology and surveillance systems. Therefore, I request a waiver of all fees associated with this request. If any fees apply, please inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request.

================================================================================

TIME FRAME:

I prefer to receive records electronically by email attachment. Florida law requires a response to this request within a reasonable time, the timeline for this request is 10 business days. If you anticipate difficulty meeting this timeline, please contact me.

If any portion of this request is denied, please:
1. Cite the specific statutory exemption being claimed for each withheld record
2. Provide a detailed explanation of why the exemption applies to the specific information being withheld
3. Indicate whether a redacted version of the record can be provided

Thank you for your assistance. Please contact me if you have any questions about this request or require clarification on any aspect of what is being sought.

Sincerely,

Kyle Searfoss

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Bill Clinton Presidential Library: Records concerning Russian Internet Adoption and Independent Digital Forums (Live journal) (Sept 2000 – Jan 2001)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request access to and copies of records within the National Security Council (NSC) and the White House Office of Records Management (WHORM) regarding the Clinton Administration’s awareness and analysis of Russian civil society’s adoption of US-based social media platforms, specifically LiveJournal ("Живой Журнал")

I. Scope of Request The time frame for this search is September 1, 2000, through January 20, 2001. I request that NARA search the following Record Groups:

NSC Intelligence Programs Directorate: Specifically files related to "Information Operations," "Cyber Policy," or "Russian Political Stability."
NSC Russian, Ukrainian, and Eurasian Affairs Directorate: Records concerning the transition from the Yeltsin to the Putin administration and the subsequent crackdown on traditional media (e.g., the NTV/Media-Most seizure).
NSC Records Management System (RMS): Search for cables and profile sheets originating from the CIA, NSA, or U.S. Embassy Moscow regarding digital dissent.

II. Specific Records Requested

Daily Intelligence Briefings: All Presidential Daily Briefs (PDBs), Senior Executive Intelligence Briefs (SEIBs), or Intelligence Summaries - of fragments thereof - that mention the growth of the Russian-language internet (Runet) or the use of "personal journaling" or "web diaries" or "online journal" software by Russian political figures, journalists, or intellectuals.

The "ZheZhe" Phenomenon: Any reports or cables discussing the relocation of Russian political discourse to servers located in the United States (specifically Danga Interactive or LiveJournal.)
Surveillance and Information Security: Any records discussing the Russian government’s (FSB) early attempts to monitor or interfere with US-hosted websites used by Russian nationals.
Staff Communications: Emails or memoranda from NSC staff (such as Jack Pritchard or Glyn Davies) regarding the "Digital Divide" in Russia or the emergence of "virtual parliaments" in Moscow.

III. Keywords for Search 

Please include the following search terms in your electronic and textual search: "LiveJournal", "Zhivoy Zhurnal", "Brad Fitzpatrick", "Danga Interactive", "online dissent", "Runet", "media-most", "virtual parliament", "web diary", "online journal", "internet diary" "weblog", "blog", "blogging", "Russian blogging", "Russian bloggers", "Живой Журнал" and "journaling software".

Format and Declassification: I request that these records be provided in electronic format (PDF). I am aware that many records in the NSC Intelligence Programs directorate may be classified. I request that these documents be subjected to a Mandatory Declassification Review (MDR) if they are found to be responsive but currently withheld under Exemption 1. If certain parts of this request or certain portions must be redacted please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

Thank you to the William J. Clinton Library, and the library's commitment to transparency.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

communications.subject: Public Records Request :: P066277-020226
communications.communication:
Dear Michael Michael: 
Our office received your open records request pursuant to Missouri's Sunshine Law, Chapter 610, RSMo. Your request has been assigned number P066277-020226. The Patrol is committed to adhering to the Sunshine Law and to ensuring that the public obtains access to open records that are not otherwise closed by law. The Sunshine Law requires each public agency to adhere to certain standards. This letter is designed to ensure that you understand our process for fulfilling your records request. Three Business Day Notice Requirement: 
The requested records are not immediately available for dissemination or inspection. The Patrol is required to notify you that additional research time will be required to fulfill the request. This correspondence satisfies the Sunshine Law's notice requirement within the required three business day period. Section 610.023.3, RSMo. 
 Additional Research Time is Required: 
The Patrol receives thousands of open records requests each month. Our Patrol Records Division personnel are dedicated to meeting the intent of Missouri's Sunshine Law and strive to respond to each request in a timely manner. The Patrol operates in all 114 Missouri counties and the independent city of St. Louis. Accordingly, many records maintained by the agency are not centrally located within, or immediately accessible to, the Patrol's Custodian of Records in Jefferson City. Our staff must research your request and ensure that we have captured all responsive records  ̶  regardless of their location within the agency. The research process is time-consuming, but we will make every effort to expedite your request. Estimated Time for Completion: 
The majority of our requests are fulfilled within thirty business days. Some requests require additional research time due to their scope or complexity. Our team will conduct an initial review of your request. If we estimate that the request will be fulfilled within thirty business days, we will not send an updated time estimate. However, if we estimate that the request will take longer than thirty business days, we will provide an updated time estimate that provides a detailed justification for the additional research time. Billing: 
As it relates to billing, Missouri law allows the Patrol to charge fees for copies and research time. Specifically, "[r]esearch time required for fulfilling records requests may be charged at the actual cost of research time." Section 610.026, RSMo. The Missouri Supreme Court recently determined that "staff time is the time required to provide access to public records maintained on computer facilities, recording tapes or disks, videotapes or films, pictures, maps, slides, graphics, illustrations or similar audio or visual items". Gross v. Parson, 624 S.W.3d 877, 884-89 (Mo. 2021) (internal quotations omitted). 
The Patrol will never bill you for redaction time or any research time conducted by our legal staff. You will only be charged for copies and staff research time as permitted by Missouri law. Please let us know if you have questions related to the billing estimate. 
Our team will forward a bill estimate to your attention once we have calculated the permissible costs and fees. The Patrol will not provide the responsive records until receipt of payment. Section 610.026.2, RSMo. 
We appreciate your patience as we review, research, and fulfill your open records request. You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you will receive an email when your request has been completed. If you wish to withdraw or clarify your request, or if you have questions, please call our office at (573) 526-6146, or (573) 526-6167. 
 
Sincerely, 
Gerard G. Callahan 
Custodian of Records
